{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 08:55:45.482758", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Diagnostic report — Clos (fat-tree) lab\nDate: (current state snapshot)\n\nScope and objective\n- Assess network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, and identify root cause(s) where present.\n- Data sources used: host interface/route outputs (ifconfig / ip addr / ip route) and FRR BGP tables (frr_get_bgp_conf) collected from the routers and hosts listed in the topology. A few active test commands (ping, vtysh -c) failed at the tooling layer and are noted.\n\nHigh-level summary / conclusion\n- Control-plane (BGP) appears healthy and converged: all expected /24 host subnets (10.X.Y.0/24) are present in the BGP tables observed on super-spine, spine and leaf devices and have valid best-paths. Multipath/ECMP entries are present where expected.\n- Data-plane interfaces are up on the routers (no carrier or obvious interface errors reported); leaf routers have their host-facing /24 interfaces configured and hosts are configured with appropriate addresses and default gateway.\n- No routing blackholes or missing route advertisements were observed in the collected BGP tables.\n- No device shows administrative down or physical link error counters in the outputs gathered.\n- Tooling/measurement issues: some active tests could not be executed due to the test container not running (ping_pair/get_reachability errors) or because vtysh invocation via the used function failed. This limited active end-to-end verification (ICMP) from pc_0_0 to pc_0_1.\n\nWhat I collected (evidence)\n- Host / router interface and route snapshots:\n  - pc_0_0: eth0 = 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1 (leaf_router_0_0)\n  - leaf_router_0_0: eth8 = 10.0.0.1/24 (host-facing); many inter-router /31s on eth0..eth7\n  - leaf_router_0_1: eth8 = 10.0.1.1/24 (host-facing); many inter-router /31s on eth0..eth7\n  - spine_router_0_0 / spine_router_0_1 / super_spine_router_0: many /31 inter-router addresses consistent with topology\n- FRR BGP tables (summary results per device):\n  - super_spine_router_0 (AS 65000): shows learned /24s from spines and selects best next-hops; multiple alternatives present.\n  - spine_router_0_0 (AS 65100) and spine_router_0_1 (AS 65101): show the 10.0.X.0/24 and 10.1/10.2/10.3 prefixes, with ECMP/multipath nexthops to super-spine and leaf paths; each spine has best-paths for various prefixes.\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (AS 65200) and leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201): advertise their local /24s (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 respectively) and have BGP-learned routes for the other leaf/pod prefixes.\n- Routing table evidence examples:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 ip route shows 10.0.1.0/24 … 10.3.7.0/24 as BGP routes via the inter-router nexthop on the spine-facing interface (consistent with EBGP behavior).\n  - BGP tables include all 32 expected /24 routes (the environment uses multiple pods/prefixes and the tables show the full set).\n\nFindings and interpretation\n1) BGP convergence / route distribution\n   - Finding: All expected /24 subnets are present in the BGP tables on multiple devices (super-spine, spines, leaves). Where multiple AS-paths exist, best paths are consistently selected and multipath entries are present where configured/expected.\n   - Interpretation: The EBGP peering relationships are established and exchanging prefixes. The super-spine-to-spine and spine-to-leaf advertisement chains are functioning.\n\n2) Interface and link state\n   - Finding: All router interfaces shown in the ifconfig/ip addr outputs are UP and have IPs assigned. There are no RX/TX errors or carrier/collision counters reported on router interfaces.\n   - Interpretation: No physical-layer interface failures were observed in the collected snapshots.\n\n3) Host configuration and traffic\n   - Finding: pc_0_0 is configured 10.0.0.2/24 with default gw 10.0.0.1. The leaf_router_0_0 host-facing IF is 10.0.0.1. Packet counters on host-facing IFs show zero traffic (RX/TX 0) for those interfaces in the router snapshots; pc_0_0 interface also shows zero RX/TX.\n   - Interpretation: Hosts are configured, but there is no observed traffic in the snapshots. That may be because no application/traffic was generated during collection or because active tests could not be run due to tooling issues. The lack of traffic counters alone is not an error.\n\n4) Active test/tooling limitations\n   - Finding: Attempt to run reachability/ping tests (get_reachability, ping_pair) returned container errors: \"container ... is not running\". Also vtysh via \"vtysh -c 'show ...'\" failed in one call but the alternative method (frr_get_bgp_conf) returned BGP tables successfully.\n   - Interpretation: The lab/test harness prevented running certain active tests. This limited explicit L3 end-to-end verification (ICMP between PCs) from being executed via those functions.\n\nAnomalies / deviations detected\n- No network-level anomalies detected (no missing prefixes, no BGP session flaps shown in the static snapshots, no interface errors).\n- Minor operational/tool anomalies:\n  - The tool-runner reported a non-running container which prevented:\n    - get_reachability and ping_pair from completing.\n    - One attempt at \"vtysh -c 'show ...'\" returned \"% Unknown command: vtysh -c show\" (likely because the wrapper did not accept the vtysh invocation format); however, frr_get_bgp_conf succeeded.\n  - Some host data retrieval (pc_0_1) initially failed on one call because of the same container/exec issue; later the leaf and other router outputs were available and consistent.\n\nLocalization (faulty devices or suspect components)\n- No router or interface shows configuration or operational state that indicates a fault based on the collected outputs.\n- The only “fault” observed is at the test/execution environment level (container/exec errors) that prevented active probing. That is an instrumentation fault, not a network topology fault.\n- Candidate devices to check further if active failures are observed in operations:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 (host-facing interfaces): they are configured and should be checked with live ICMP from respective PCs if further verification is required; currently counters show no traffic.\n  - Any spine or super-spine if BGP session counters or flaps are observed during continuous monitoring — none were evident in the snapshots.\n\nRoot-cause assessment\n- Based on the available evidence there is no network root cause to identify (no device is in a failed state, and routes are fully propagated). The only root cause for inability to actively test host-to-host connectivity is the test harness/container execution errors that prevented running ping/reachability tools from within this environment.\n\nAdditional notes / evidence snippets\n- pc_0_0: ip route shows default via 10.0.0.1\n- leaf_router_0_0: eth8 = 10.0.0.1/24; ip route contains BGP-learned 10.0.1.0..10.3.7.0 via spine nexthop\n- leaf_router_0_1: eth8 = 10.0.1.1/24; ip route contains BGP-learned 10.0.0.0..10.3.7.0 via spine nexthop\n- BGP tables on super-spine/spines/leaves show full set of 32 /24 routes and appropriate AS-paths\n\nRecommended next diagnostic actions (if you want to continue troubleshooting)\n- (Not a remediation) Execute active connectivity tests once the container/exec environment is repaired: ping from pc_0_0 to pc_0_1, traceroute to confirm the forwarding path, and re-run vtysh show ip bgp summary on each router to verify session state and uptime.\n- Collect FRR BGP neighbor summary (sessions state) and check BGP session counters if intermittent issues occur.\n- If host-facing traffic should be present but is not, verify host OS and applications and try local ping to gateway from each PC.\n\nFinal assessment (concise)\n- Network control plane (BGP) is converged and route propagation is complete across super-spine, spine and leaf routers.\n- No router or interface shows signs of failure in the captured snapshots.\n- The only confirmed problem is tooling/measurement failure that prevented live ICMP tests; no network root-cause was identified from the collected data.\n\nIf you want, I can:\n- Retry specific active tests (ping/traceroute) if you re-run the environment so the container execs succeed.\n- Run per-router BGP neighbor summary (vtysh) and interface counters if you want deeper per-session diagnostics.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 69436, "output_tokens": 4692, "total_tokens": 74128, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 69248}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2688}}}
